1202–1250","1202–1250":"1202–1250","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1226–1261":"1226–1261","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1170–1249":"1170–1249","1178–1250":"1178–1250","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1261":"1261","1170":"1170","5 December 1202":"5 December 1202","1249":"1249","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","about 1226":"about 1226","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","Walton Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Walton, Yorkshire, England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Walton,East Riding,Yorkshire,England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Askham Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fairfax","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for someone with beautiful long hair, from Middle English <i>fair fax</i> ‘beautiful tresses’. This was a common descriptive phrase in Middle English: the alliterative poem <i>Sir Gawain and the Green Knight</i> refers to ‘fair fanning fax’ encircling the shoulders of the doughty warrior.","History: Thomas Fairfax (1693–1781), an army officer from Leeds Castle, Kent, England, first came to VA in 1735 and settled on maternal estates there as a proprietor in 1747."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":12,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":21,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fairfax II was born on 5 December 1202, in Walton, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Fairfax, was 32 and his mother, Alice de Bugthorpe, was 25. He married Mary Flower in 1249. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. In 1249, at the age of 47, his occupation is listed as high bailiff of york. He died in 1250, in Walton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"5 December 1202–1250":"5. detsember 1202–1250","1202–1250":"1202–1250","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1226–1261":"1226–1261","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1170–1249":"1170–1249","1178–1250":"1178–1250","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1261":"1261","1170":"1170","5 December 1202":"5. detsember 1202","1249":"1249","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","about 1226":"umbes 1226","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","Walton Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Ingli